==English==
===Etymology===
From Old (and modern) French [[contrister]], from Latin [[contristare]], from [[con-]] + [[tristis]] ‘sad’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/kənˈtrɪst/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# ''(transitive, obsolete)'' To make [[sad]], to [[upset]].
#:*'''1761''': with such weak nerves and spirits, and in the condition I am in at present, ’twould be as much as my life was worth, to deject and '''contrist''' myself with so bad and melancholy an account — Laurence Sterne, ''The Life & Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman'', vol. 3 (Penguin 2003, p. 179)